04647nam a2200757Ia 9780228021650DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280216507 a10.1515/97802280216502doi  a(DE-B1597)679703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPT2440.N72bZ56 2024 7aPHI0460002bisacsh04a193223/eng/202405011 aBéland, Martine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNietzsche as Stylist :bAesthetics and Philosophy /cMartine Béland. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPrologue: When in Weimar -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction — Elements of Style: Nietzsche’s Aesthetic Legacy -- t1 A Shooting Star: Nietzsche, Profession, and Vocation -- t2 Against Opera: A War on Entertainment -- t3 Nuts and Bolts: Inside the Factory of Schola -- t4 The Individualist: On Becoming Who You Are -- t5 A Portrait of the Philosopher as Artist -- t6 His Best Prose: Nietzsche’s Prefaces -- t7 An Unlikely Hero: Nietzsche’s Dashes -- tEpilogue — Aesthetic Reception: On Reading and Curating Nietzsche -- tA Very Short Chronology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough he had a short career, German philosopher Friedrich Nietzsche was a prolific writer, publishing seventeen books in the span of seventeen years. Convinced that “style must live,” he focused obsessively on a wide variety of factors that could potentially affect readers’ uptake of his work, from the craft of preface writing to punctuation choices to the aesthetics of book jackets.Nietzsche as Stylist traces the emergence of the philosopher’s idiosyncratic writing style as he experimented with various rhetorical approaches. Introducing a contextual and historical sensibility to readings of Nietzsche’s published and unpublished works – as well as his correspondence, his journal entries, and other documents he interacted with, such as reviews of his work – the book highlights how Nietzsche’s style evolved in relation to his life and world. Martine Béland situates his writings within contemporaneous debates about the professionalization of academia: by resisting what he felt was an anti-philosophical climate, Nietzsche developed a synesthetic and performative style, hoping that his philosophical ideas could engage diverse readers in multiple ways.Through careful stylistic and contextual analysis, Nietzsche as Stylist explores how Nietzsche cultivated skills as a rhetorician and a writer to bring philosophy into a wider field of attention, thought, and experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aArthur Schopenhauer.  aBruno Latour.  aGermany.  aRalph Waldo Emerson.  aRichard Wagner.  aWeimar.  aabstractionism.  aaesthetics.  aaporia.  aart.  acontingency.  acritical music.  ahistory.  aindividualism.  aliterature.  ametaphor.  aperspectivism.  aphilology.  apreface.  areception studies.  arhetoric.  astylistics.  avocation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228021650?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228021650423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228021650/original  a978-3-11-140848-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles